 people would be paying well more than an item is worth just to make sure they get it, and others would get items for pennies.  But I do think the bid system would work great for any item that is going to rot.  I couldn;t believe some of the stuff that I saw rotting on some of Vis' raids, but people weren;t willing to spend the points on some items.  So I would rather see someone win a 6 point item with a bid of 0.5 than see it rot. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/ugurunt.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gurunt</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#0000FF>(1/15/02 5:12:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub75.ezboard.com/fwraith27960general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=655.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Point System</span><hr size=1> <br>
Yeah, problems come up in certain situatiosn in both systems.<br>
<br>
What I liked about the points system is.. it's ultimately the player that chooses to burn the points or hold back or wait.  <br>
<br>
When dealing with the class-specific stuff with only one player.. what if the rogue dagger drops for 6 points, but the rogue is only 4 points ahead of the next closest player, and the rogue wants to stay ahead to bid on some other item on a mob we'll kill next.... we let the dagger rot?  We force the rogue to get the dagger at the expense of the item he really wants? <br>
<br>
<br>
Those are lose-lose situation, niether system can handle it fairly without letting the item rot.... but IMO if we have someone making  a habit of being the only or one of the only members of thier class regularly, that's a whole different issue <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/umurghkhor.showPublicProfile?language=EN>murghkhor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Officer</span><br> <font color=#0000FF>(1/15/02 9:19:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub75.ezboard.com/fwraith27960general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=655.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Point System</span><hr size=1> <br>
Gurunt,<br>
<br>
actually you keep coming to this one example that you use everywhere of &quot;holding back&quot; points and how that's a big flaw. If you notice ppl do that even in officer awards. Tons of ppl when asked if they want a certain item, reply by saying no they want to hold you for &quot;that one&quot; or something. In essence it's the same thing. <br>
<br>
If someone is not willing to spend the 6 points for the dagger then either<br>
1. He doesnt care for having the dagger<br>
or<br>
2. The dagger is overvalued.<br>
<br>
Feedback on loot item prices is also something I would like, same with mob values. I believe the points system comes closest to capturing a perfect system (Perfect being officer award with everything accounted, like even what time everyone arrives or who they port to bring to raids etc, executed fairly). I still see items rotting on raids (remember in VP) becasue noone cared enough to even loot the item, they didnt even want it for their twinks. <br>
<br>
Let me pose a scenario and you tell me what the solution is.<br>
<br>
There is only 1 int caster on a ToV raid who doesnt have ToV Robe. Lets say it's Sandy. Silk robe drops. She wants to hold out for the Velk Robe. What should happen. What you are proposing is that she should get to loot the silk robe somehow and still get the Velk Robe later if it drops, even if there is a wizard at the velk raid who also needs a tov robe or better and who deserves it just a little bit less than Sandy. Now if Sandy looted the ToV robe you think the other wizard wont feel cheated ? What system would work best in this scenario. What would you do in the perfect system (a perfect officer award) ?<br>
<br>
I still think a bidding system would fail since it would certainly make the second wizard feel cheated. But a point system would only endanger a loot item rotting, not anyone feeling cheated. Does this make sense ?<br>
<br>
-Desi <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uyasunaga.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yasunaga</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#0000FF>(1/15/02 10:55:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub75.ezboard.com/fwraith27960general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=655.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Point System</span><hr size=1> I also do not agree with the bidding system (even though I play only part-time and prolly won't accumulate enough points to buy a rusty dagger <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) As sad as it may seem, I think items MUST rot if no one spends the required points to purchase the item.  Otherwise, the whole premise of the system goes down the tubes.<br>
