Jama <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/utalidorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Talidorn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#0000FF>(1/25/02 1:43:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub75.ezboard.com/fwraith27960general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=655.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Aguilera has it right...</span><hr size=1> I think Aguilera had it right when she suggested having a fixed point system that fell back to a bid system if no one bid on the loot. I only see this system being fair for no drop and non-mq-able items though. That means that if people did not want an MQ-able or droppable item enough, then it could go to someone else in the future who wanted to spend those points. Now, if the item is no drop and non-mq'able, then opening it up for bids would simply set the price of the item within a specific boundary--i.e. from 0.1 to the original price of the item. <br>
<br>
People might argue that this is unfair in situations in which a class specific item drops and only one of those classes is around to bid on it. I would say that that person is simply lucky enough to be on a raid under such circumstances. Admittedly, this system would be slightly disadvantageous to classes that are required to be at raids en masse--llike clerics, warriors, etc. What you could do to help prevent people from taking advantage of this system would be to have a shadow point count as well--that is, have two point counters--one counter that tells how much they actually spent on items and another that is half of the item's estimated worth (or the amount they bid on the item--whichever is greater). Now, if a person has a lot of points but a huge shadow point count, then if an item drops that he/she can use as well as one of the more popular classes can use, then that person can bid on the item, but his/her total points for tiebreaks could come from the shadow count. <br>
<br>
I think that this system would minimize rottage. And it also addresses the concern of having a bid system that would force one rogue to pay the full price but would allow the other one to get it for nearly nothing. The second rogue gets it for nearly nothing, but he/she also ls at a disadvantage in tie-breaks later on.<br>
<br>
-Talidorn<br>
